#TeaganAir
The flight logbook has officially been put into use. I've already recorded 2.3 hours of flight time ^_^
#TeaganAir
If you let me describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a motorcycle, all-terrain vehicle, and a boat at 4000 feet high.
On the ground, conditions change rapidly. Due to a certain degree of instability, motorcycles or all-terrain vehicles are required.
By the way, you might not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the control stick. It uses rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
When flying in the air, you will experience turbulence and shaking, feeling much like riding a boat on the water. Although you can control the airplane, sometimes the air currents can make you a bit disoriented. Therefore, you need to adapt to flying in the air just as sailors adapt to sailing on the sea.
By the way, there's also a random fun fact about this:
Flying is very physically exhausting. Today, my back and legs are really sore, as if I had gone to the gym and worked out.
This is nothing like a casual drive on a Sunday. From the perspective of a novice, it seems more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, happy Saturday. Welcome to 4,000 feet up in the air.
Tomorrow I will fly again, and we need to practice stalls and slow flight.
Today's weather wasn't very stable, but it was super interesting. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 miles per hour, while the airspeed was still at 65 miles per hour.
The weather is clear today. Although there's a bit of haze in the high altitude, the view is still great.
FlightAware data track.
